supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil, 1-756. Intermittent earlier modern foliation, incorrect and struck through. Historia (del.) legenda de sancto Theobaldo

collation.signatures:
Quire signatures on quires 5-24, 26-27, 31-33, 37-64, and 66. The quire signatures reveal that the manuscript has been reorganised at least once. Quires 5-24 and 37-64 display a complete series of quire numbers running from Ius
to xviiius
, revealing this as one unit (with the Proper of Saints following directly after the Proper of Time). The signatures on quire 26-27, 31-33, and 66 align with a series in which each quire signature is 2 less of the current number of quires, which would be explained if, for example, the current quires 1-3 were once one quire (1-3 = 1; 4 = 2; 5 = 3 etc.). At some point, the current quires 25-36 were inserted into the unit which consisted of the current quires 5-24 and 37-64, and new quire numbers applied. As only one folio of the last quire (66, signature 64) remains, and the last folio of the inserted unit, , carries the donation note of Mathias Hendel, a likely scenario would seem to be that the current quires 25-36 originally made up the last part of the manuscript, with whatever came between the rest of what is now quire 66 and what is now quire 25 having been lost.

p.note: Top left corner, in pencil in a modern hand: the current signum, Kungl. Bibl. A 175.

Top of page, in ink by a modern hand: Kongl. Bibl. 1734 års Kat. Theol. in fol. no 45.; centre page, in ink over 4 lines by a modern hand: Ordo siue Breuiarium de Ecclesiasticis Obseruacionibus quid legendum aut cantandum sit per circulum anni secundum Patauiensem Ecclesiam MScr de anno MCCLXXXV.; a modern hand has put an exclamation mark in parentheses following the year and below it a question mark; below, in pencil and square brackets by a modern hand: PASSAU.
Column a: an abecedarium in the scribal hand; column b: a verse on the properties of wine with an addition of two lines by Tibullus in a later hand below.

binding.p:
The binding consists of two parts: only the is original; the has been taken from a different medieval binding and added later; its wooden board is thinner and slightly smaller than that of the . The original binding displays at least two contemporary layers: first, red leather over wooden boards. Over this, a second cover, of brown leather, has been added and is now glued down. The first layer of leather appears to cover a smaller area than the second, and the wooden board has been cracked in two and repaired. The two layers may correspond to the addition of several quires and reorganisation of the original structure which is revealed by the quire signatures. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Originally, two clasps and straps; centre and corner bosses. (on red cover), in ink on a paper label: Missale 180; stamped in gold: A 175; in ink on a parchment label: No 45; in ink on a parchment label on top of the previous label: e. 30. 5. 4
; in ink on a parchment label (e) 35
, and below, 137.

decoNote.p: : a blind-tooled double-outline frame, inside of which two double-outline bands form the shape of an X. : 3 bands of 4 blind-tooled parallel lines forming a frame, inside of which bands of 3 blind-tooled parallel lines form a pattern of lozenges; inside of these, blind-stamped flowers and medallions alternating between the Agnus Dei and a double-headed eagle.

binding.condition: has been reinforced with leather at the and corners. On the , windows have been cut out at the top and bottom of the second layer of leather, revealing the first leather cover and labels underneath. is heavily worn and torn in places, with the red leather showing around the edges. Of the clasps, straps, and bosses, only two plates remain on the front cover, and, on the back, a stud and short stubs of the straps. Boards exposed at .

origin.p: Austria , 1375. In a verse on , the compiler of the manuscript, Mathias Gallulus (Mathias Hendel), chaplain of Duke Leopold III of Austria and dean of the college of St Mary's church at Perchtoldsdorf (Perchtoldsdorf, Austria), describes his text-collecting activities and his reasons for compiling the texts, and states that the book was finished in the year , having taken two years to complete, and in his donation note on , he states that he gathered material for the book for thirty years or more.

provenance.p: On , Mathias Gallulus records his donation of the manuscript to the church of St Mary at Perchtoldsdorf and its dean on April 13, 1382 (lxxxii). It was still in the possession of the church at Perchtoldsdorf in /, when Thomas Ebendorfer von Haselbach (d. 1464), theologian and historian at the university of Vienna as well as dean of the college of St Mary's church at Perchtoldsdorf, added a couple of notes on .

acquisition.p: The manuscript was most likely taken as spoils of war during the Thirty Years' War. It is listed on p. 67 (first entry) in Vossius's catalogue of 1651 (U 202:1), as no. 137 in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 (U118:10), as no. 35 (recording also the former signum 137) in Jaches's catalogue of 1698 (U 122), as Theol. in fol. no. 45 in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), and as e. 30. 5, no. 4, in Hammarsköld's catalogue of the 19th century (U 133). The signum 180 found on the has not been identified.

note.p: : translation of St Virgil (26 Sep.; addition);

The calendar also records a large number of feasts which are not otherwise typical for Passau, e.g. St Jovinus (2 Mar.), St Florentius (6 Apr.; cf. ), St Ubaldus (16 May; cf. ), St Brendan (17 May), St Albanus (21 June), St Louis of France (25 Aug.), St Verena and St Prisca (1 Sept.; cf. and ), St Maternus (13 Spetember), St Himerius (12 Nov.), and St Longinus (1 Dec.). Several are feasts common in Bohemia - e.g. the translation of St Wenceslaus (4 Mar.), St Sigismund (1 May; festum fori), St Stanislaus ( rather than the translation of St Stephen, May 8), St Ladislaus (27 June; addition), St Procopius (4 Aug.; addition), and St Ludmilla (16 Sept.) - and several are common to a large number of German dioceses, e.g. St Polycarp (26 Jan.), St Germanus (31 July), and St Magnus (19 Aug.) The calendar also records, as an addition, a Dedicacio in Mawrbach on May 17.
Each month also includes a cisiojanus for the month in question.

supportDesc.foliation: Near contemporary foliation, 1-14, on , which continues with 15-253 on breaks off and then picks up again with 254-281 at , skips the blank leaves (), and continues with 283-614 on .
supportDesc.condition: Holes from corner bosses and clasps on and . Occasional holes and traces of stitching, e.g. and , with the thread preserved in several places, e.g. and . The leaf between and torn out. The bottom edges and corners of (approx. the extent of the ferial psalter) particularly dirty due to heavy use. On , the ink has bled somewhat.

layout.note: Guidelines and ruling in brown or black ink.

handDesc.p: Two principal textualis hands can be distinguished, with possible further subdivisions (cf. for example , and ).

The second main hand (Hand 3) is also found in Mathias Hendel's donation note on beginning Ego mathias dictus Hendel, but he is possibly the scribe behind several of the hands; the other note mentioning him by name () is, for example, in a cursiva antiquior.
handDesc.handNote: Gothic cursive. ( Thomas Ebendorfer von Haselbach )

p.note: Numerous additions of liturgical material, often in the scribal hand. On , the addition has been erased, crossed out, and marked with the warning caue.
Occasional corrections, often in the scribal hand.
Notes by Thomas Ebendorfer von Haselbach .
Top margin in red ink by the scribe ( Mathias Hendel Gallulus ?), various exhortations to the reader to take care with the book.
In the margins, drolleries in the form of faces, animals, and some objects.
Rubrics noted in the margin in a separate medieval hand.
Accompanying the manuscript is an envelope containing several scraps of paper, some with writing in different medieval hands, probably having served as bookmarks.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black or brown ink; rubrics and instructions in red; capitals touched in red.

decoNote.p: : inhabited foliate opening initial A over 11 lines in a purple and lilac floral pattern with white highlights and a border of green flower stems with flowers in blue and orange extending from the letter body. In the top counter space against a blue background, Christ wearing an orange mantle and carrying a book; in the bottom counter space against a blue background with a stylised floral pattern, a monk in a light yellow robe kneeling in prayer, surrounded by rocks and trees. : penwork initial I over 11 lines in blue with flourishing in red. , , , , , , , , : decorated initials over 4-11 lines in blue ink with various shapes inlaid in gold leaf and sgraffed patterns against a background of red pen-flourishing ( and inverted colour scheme) and a border of red, blue, and gold pen-flourishing extending along the margin or between the columns and punctuated by flowers in red or blue or tendrils in gold. Initial missing on . , , , : decorated initials over 4-6 lines in blue ink with various shapes inlaid in gold leaf with sgraffed patterns against a background of red pen-flourishing and a border of red pen-flourishing extending along the margins or between the columns ( : inverted colour scheme). : plain initials over 2-3 lines in red ink. : plain initials over 1 line in red ink. (Q5-8), (Q14), (Q16-18), (Q34), (Q65): pen-flourished initials over 2-3 lines alternating in blue and red ink with flourishing in the contrasting colour. (Q9-13), (Q15), (Q19-33), (Q35-64): plain initials over 2-3 lines alternating in blue and red ink (between and only red).
